      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>14 threads, <a href=journal.html?user=46685&start=0>1</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></form><ul><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101046531183901></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101046531183901><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=101046531183901>Karnor's Castle 001 an Introduction</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=101046531183901#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=46685><span id=Scholar>Laleldil</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>78 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Jan 7th 11:48 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.97]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I am in a quandary: Do I place this long and perhaps tedious posting here or in my journal.&nbsp;&nbsp;Ultimately I have decided to place it in the journal due to its length.  I can only hope those interested will find this information.  I have been in KC nearly 24 hours straight, yes in one sitting at the keyboard. (Next quest, of course, is increasing spousal faction.)  The information I present here is what I (emphasize I) found in this adventure and a few previous adventures.  My first of which is posted in this site.  As far as accuracy, I will try to be as accurate as I can be.  As far as mob and loot tables, I'll leave that to the parser readers.<br><br>For you that are first entering KC, note that there are two ways close together to enter this dungeon.  From the Dreadlands zone you have the option of entering in the right or left side.  Please enter the dungeon using the left entrance.  There is a possibility you will live a little longer.  This is also the first of many times you will be told about the left.  Left always zone left, in or out of KC, zone left.  There is only one left.  I do not care how you remember this but left. Left the KC to sell.  Left all alone.  Not the hand with which I eat my food, assuming you are right handed.  LEFT! ZONE LEFT!<br><br>EDIT for clarification: Please when you are in Dreadlands use the left as you look to the KC zone.  From the KC perspective, thus looking in the opposite direction you will be coming into the right side.  As you visualize this from KC perspective the RIGHT side is the side people are coming in or are recovering.  Should you leave the KC zone use the LEFT side, again this is from KC perspective.  The reason this is so vital to understand is that Trains are very frequent and by zoning in the wrong side you may find yourself dead before you can escape.  Also you can lose great player faction should you err and train the players that are trying to recover and rez in the right hall.  You have been warned as best I can explain this.  Always zone using your left, whether in Dreadlands or KC.<br><br>You have entered KC using the LEFT entrance available from Dreadlands and probably see scattered about more than one or two corpses.  If it is a busy day, at the LEFT wall of this area sits many players LEFT naked or LEFT wanting to get into groups.  Following the hallway it turns right and then there is an area called the entrance which goes to your LEFT across bridges and through towers, but if you continue this initial walk straight you will turn and come to the exit that is called LEFT.  Zone out LEFT.  You have LEFT KC.  When you go into KC you will eventually get a train, take the train out the left side.  If you do not take the train to the LEFT exit but take it to the other zone line, most likely you will be LEFT all alone forever!  LEFT.<br><br>As far as classes and levels?  I imagine there are better classes then others, but still there MAY be a time and place for every class.  The ones I see most easily finding groups are Clerics and Enchanters.  Both are nearly absolutely essential for adventuring much past the moat camps.  Warriors, Monks, Shamans could possible be the next easiest to find groups.  Rouges, Paladins, Druids probably fall in about here and the Wizards, Magicians unfortunately seem to find it the hardest to find groups.  Some classes I am simply to unfamiliar with to list such as Necromancers and SK's.  Rangers are useable at times but the eggshell armor allowed to them is a cleric's nightmare, though a Ranger who KNOWS his class, limitations, and abilities can prove invaluable. Though of course there may already be a sufficient quantity of your particular class at any time.  As in all zones some classes can get into groups younger than others.  Will you instantly get in a group, do not count on it, but you should be able to if you are patient.<br><br>The first 'camp' location is the entrance.  With the dungeon empty of all other players this is of course the safest place to camp.  It can be held forever.  Add one other group camping anywhere, even a solid group of 60's would find it a challenge to remain in this camp.  Remember BLACKBURROW?  Psshaw!  That aint nothing!  At the merest mention of train, immediately move away from the camp and plopping your arses done on or near the wall and better closer to the point you entered the castle.  Naturally if you are a high enough group you can bust up some trains, but then obviously you should not be camping this location.<br><br>The entrance camp has a further characteristic of being the beginning of nearly every camp. You want to camp LCY?  YOU WILL most likely start your camp busting at this entrance.<br><br>Camp level 2.  The left moat.  Just past the first two sentries you can turn left or right holding tightly to the wall and set up camps in the corners.  Generally you are safe from any trains, except of course your train.  As an expert at meditation, I chose to plop down as far into the corners as possible.  I cringe every time I see someone else dangle their legs over the edge of land and into the moat.  You will find you can give yourself something to do.  It is the same when your group has decided to do battle at the narrowest pieces of land or standing toe to toe at the water's edge.  Things swim in that water and will happily camp YOU.  But using some common sense this is probably the safest camp to hold for an extended amount of time.  Nearly every class can benefit a four hour camp here.  With knowledgeable healers, you can even do this camp I believe without clerics or enchanters.<br><br>Pull mobs from the water, pull the two sentries, pull from right moat area, pull from the bottom of dog tower, possibly even pull from the bottom of the skel tower.  Assuming no one else is camping any of the areas.  You can pull live dogs from the water and dead things that need to be made more dead.  Dog tower is live dogs and skel tower is dead things.  Will you get awesome loot? No.  You will get experience in a controlled fashion.  You have a possibility of getting some decent things, but that should not be your reason for camping there.  Perhaps most utilized for groups that are waiting for their desired camp to open or by the intelligent younger players learning more about the zone.<br><br>Third camp right moat.  This ranks very close to left moat as desirable for younger players.  However it is sometimes utilized by higher players to begin pulling from the basement.  Since I do NOT pull, I have no warning to give you about what you will find when the puller swims under the water and enters the basement.  One point worth mentioning is the peculiar pathing the basement mobs take when they are pulled.  They land much closer to the corner (where you would camp if you were on the other moat) then you might expect them to.  Please camp directly in the corner if you are not pulling the basement.  If you are pulling the basement settle yourselves with the meditators about 2/3's to 3/4's away from the corner with the melee's between the sitters and the corner.  Allow the mob to climb onto the land and the melees can do their thing while clerics, enchanters, wizards etc can do the things we do behind the fight.<br><br>Fourth camp Dog Tower most commonly called Cappy's, Captains, or a variation of any of the above.  Cross the first bridge and you have entered the tower.  I know there are stairs off to the right and the camps that I have been on have been at the top of those stairs.  This is not a real safe place to learn about this zone but it is the best place to get a feel about this zone.  From my limited exposure to this zone I know of no location that does not have spawn points that aggro where ever you plan on camping.  In other words, though I am not the wisest of the zone, I know no place you can simply sit without something spawning near enough to aggro you.<br><br>The Captain inhabits this occasionally and is probably the first named mob people desire to take on.  His loot is nice, but then so is his amount of hitpoints.  A careful puller can keep the group well occupied.  A cleric is a wise choice to have, though an enchanter can be replaced by a ranger and possibly others that can ghetto park.  I do Know that a ranger keeping his eyes open and casting harmony on wandering mobs is nice.  Particularly if you are just not ready for that third mob to join the fracas.  Here, like in the Dreadlands, aggro control is a premium if you wish to allow your cleric to heal you and not run out of mana.  Please begin now to ask that only one of the group get the aggro and keep it until near death.  These critters hit hard enough that it becomes a Cleric's nightmare watching the aggro make cycles through the members of his party.  Eventually he has to decide who to heal and who will risk death.  All that is negligible if you the melee will control your aggro.  By letting the one meat shield absorb the damage a 45 cleric will find it nearly a breeze to keep everything running smooth.  By using celestial heal and an occasional greater healing all is peachy keen.  Start making your cleric use superior healing on five other players and you will be the next train asked (shouted) TRAIN LEFT.  Exit this camp by going down the stairs and crossing the bridge to the entrance camp and turn left.  I hate to say you need to turn right to actually zone.  But please remember left at the T.<br><br>I have yet to group with a damage caster in KC.  Damage dealt by these mobs can be high.  Get a pair of these Doggies on a nuker and there will not be time enough to save them.  If you enter KC with the intent of blasting the mob, know your class.  Wait to make that Nuke the ending of that dog's life.  If you are impatient and nuke instantly the group should just disband your corpse and leave you LEFT alone.<br><br>This camp is not too difficult for new players entering the castle to meet up with a group in its camp location.  With pullers frequently pulling the downstairs and entrance you can fairly safely get to the group.  Perhaps even your puller has been clearing the floor you are on and bring the lower level up to you using stairs on the other side of the tower.<br><br>A few cautions.  I would recommend you do not fight to close to the wall at the top of the stairs as it is open to allow you to fall off the wall and into the moat or on the ground below.  Nor would I recommend this as the preferred method to escape the tower.  The doggies will still attempt to deal with you and your swimming may not be that great so you could not only have your little train waiting for you on the bridge but have a fresh train on your tail from the water.  For the ones that meditate, sit down on the floor along the wall to the right of the stairs or on the stairs nearer the top, again using the outside wall.  You can almost see the spawn points at these locations and hopefully your melee classes are between you and them.  Since I have not scouted out that floor I do not know if there is a better site to camp the Captain.  Perhaps I will get someone to make me invisible and look for myself.  What I would prefer if it were possible would be to find a camp more in the center of  the tower on the wall over the moat and bridge closest to the Castle proper.  Perhaps there is an area more open to allow greater visibility and thus more warning when doggies begin to pop.  However the top of the stairs is a doable camp location IF you can control the adds you can get.<br><br>Fifth camp skeleton tower.  I have read that this is a camp location, however  I have not heard of it being camped and also obviously I was never involved in a camp there.  I believe the tower to be filled with a collection of dead that needs dying and I am guessing it is slightly more difficult as some of the dead have pets.  Whether there are dead with pets in the tower, I can not factually say.<br><br>The Castle Proper.<br><br>The sixth camp site and the one most chosen for its variety and possible loot is the left court yard.  LCY.  The place to set camp is in the corner diagonally from the structure that is the stairs going up.  You can not see the stairs as the stairs are on the backside and curve around counter clockwise.  You might see the top of the stairs from the LCY but, in truth, I never looked.  Actually I guess I should say that I do not remember seeing them as I have hunted there in a group a couple of times.  I do not remember a spawn directly in that corner, however there are several spawns in the courtyard and they are a mixture of live and dead.<br><br>To get to this camp site start at the entrance camp and begin pulling.  The sentries right there, then the doggies in the lower part of their tower, then begin the extraction of the mob from the chosen courtyard.  When the courtyard is empty or only one or two left that you know your group can handle at one time, then bring your group into the courtyard and into the correct corner.<br><br>Pulling.  I again must advise that I am a cleric, thus seldom ever pull.  However, again assuming nothing else is camped, you can pull from the RCY, the skel tower, the dog tower, and the opening in the wall near where the stairs go up.  You will get a wide variety of creatures.  And if you are not careful you will soon get more than you can handle.  Though I do not know why,  in my camps of LCY no one pulled down the stairs.  I believe that this would be a good place to pull from also.  There is a mob just near the top of those stairs and a lookout is sometimes a short distance beyond that.<br><br>As far as individual mob, the one most likely to need special attention is the Spectral  Curator.  This seems to be a priest class mob that can cast complete heal.  It can also debuff your group, though it is not a group debuff.  Personally when a Curator is pulled I stand and keep it targeted ready to break any casting on his part using the three stuns I have memmed.  I try to use the lowest stun first, then progress up the level of stuns, since he can begin to cast again before the normal stun has become available to reuse.  For the shorter time of casting I simply wait to read that a Spectral Curator begins to cast, when I do not have that spell available because it has not refreshed in time I use the next one up.  Since I use my two highest stuns and the lowest stun, should I feel the Curator is going to cast before the other two have become available for recasting, I begin to cast before he begins to cast by guestimation.   Keeping this fellow from casting makes the cleric&amp;#8217;s need to heal his groupmates much less and shortens the time of the fight considerably.<br><br>Another word of warning.  When you begin to run with your train, please make sure you do have sow.  That is something everyone should have at all times, as far as I can see.  And as you begin to run, be aware the jutting of the wall makes it slightly less obvious where you should turn right and onto the bridge.  Running to the camp the bridge seems very wide.  Running to the zone with a gaggle of dead and live chasing you, you may be very surprised to find you have passed the opening and are now standing in RCY and a fresh supply of mob eagerly wanting you.  Again take your train left at the entrance camp.  Shouting train is nice, even appreciated by all, however it happens so frequently that those at the entrance have already been trained several times and should be ever vigilant of the activity coming across the bridges to them.<br><br>A second word of caution.  LCY is the path of most trains coming from the castle.  You may find every thing is going just fine and suddenly find yourselves surrounded by a half dozen or more irritated mobs.  That is perhaps the greatest drawback to camping LCY.<br><br>Now you could have chosen to camp the RCY.  Unlike LCY this is an open room with a door on one side near the corner, a narrow opening to the moat, and a balcony of sorts on the moat wall.  There is a spawn in every corner, one in the center of the moat wall, and a spawn in the moat wall.  I again do not pull so not sure what exactly is beyond the door, though the puller brings dogs and dead from there.  The construct and the hand, two different entities, that can spawn in the wall need to be pulled out of the wall in order to fight them.  I tried once for a few seconds one time and was not successful, as the room repopped before it came out of the wall.  However to pull it, I saw our puller simply stand there and eventually the hand or construct felt invited to party with us.  Set up your camp in the middle of the wall on your right as you enter.<br><br>Some dos and don&amp;#8217;ts:  Do not fight in the doorway near the way out over the bridges.  Fight only deeper in the courtyard preferably in the middle of the wall where you are camping.  Do keep casters from casting.  Things can gate and things can heal and things can do all manner of unfriendly things.  You read a caster begins to cast, stun.  Stun again.  Do not get all excited in run in a big circle in the room.  The aggro range of the mob will allow a fight right at the wall, but if you venture closer to the center of the room you will bring everything else into the fight.  They may come anyway, but your careless running will invite them much sooner.  Also you will have an enchanter.  Or you should have.  That enchanter will have his hands full simply parking all the critters that want a part of you.  Seems most every dead thing has his pet dog.  Chanters, park everything, pets included.  The rest of the party kill the parked mob in the order the chanter determines.  Please be aware that he might have six or seven things parked all over that room.  Assisting is vital.  Chose one player to be the one to attack and all others assist him.<br><br>Unlike the LCY, RCY is not in the path of all trains.  However all trains will join you should you be foolishly fighting too close to the entrance of the room.  Thus this room is easier to hold for a long time.  However also realize that people miss the way out and can bring in a host of unfriendliness into your camp.  I would chose RCY as perhaps the second best location to bring your inexperienced friends.  It is much less influenced by non-group activity.<br><br>To begin this camp, again start at the entrance and begin pulling until you can enter RCY with few enough mobs to establish yourself.  Also by pulling to the entrance, you are spacing the spawn times in a more comfortable time span.<br><br>The last camp I wish to talk about is the hand room.  Pretty much started like you would start the LCY camp.  Only when your group is assembled in LCY you will now go up the aforementioned circular stairs and the previously mentioned mob. Take the group as a whole up the stairs and kill that first one, and if the other is there take him out also.  When those are finished, you turn slightly right and find yourself in a squarish opening with the moat down there over that short wall.  Do take a few seconds to look about you!  There are several ways to turn, not all that noticeable until you are excitedly running for your life.  One thing to be aware of is that opening you will come to in your flight just before where you need to turn left and find the stairs.  You may not notice it when you came up, but you will notice it when you are running.<br><br>Once you control that square area, the puller will go down the wall aisle.  There is a short set of steps in that aisle.  I believe there is also a door, not that I opened it, but I believe that is where mob sit patiently awaiting for someone to foolishly chose those steps to med or swap spells.  You can walk the aisle and not get aggro, you can sit and have an unfriendly beating on you before you get a spell memmed.  You need to sit and med go back to the square area, or warn the others and let them kill off the two that will aggro through the walls.  However your party should not yet be moving from the square area until the hand room has been pulled.<br><br>The hand room is down that hall/aisle turn to the right at the end, the only way you can turn, then turn to the left at the first opening.  Although this begins to get a little fuzzy here, the hall will take you to a half door and then you are in the hand room.  It is square with a square depression.  Fill it with water and you would have a nice small swimming pool.  Fill it with angry foe and you are in deep doodoo. <br><br>To break this room you should have a monk.  Perhaps an enchanter could mez the hands in the room, but so far my experience has been monks pulling the hands using FD.  The times I have gone to that camp, the hands were singularly or double pulled and quickly dispatched.  Please do not do that exactly.  Pull one hand and kill it, take a minute or two, three even, and then pull the next hand. Once you have pulled three of the four hands and dispatched them, bring the group into the hand room and finish the last hand.<br><br>Unfortunately I do not know the spawn time of the hands.  I do know that each time I have been in that camp with a fast pull and camp, we have had more than we can handle holding the room.  You would be well advised to pull the room slowly and then learn the spawn time before letting the puller do his happy thing.  If you plan on being there, plan on learning the camp first.  It has always been the confusion of hands spawning just as the puller yells incoming and brings in his unfriendly that has caused the camp to collapse in ignominy.  With two clerics and an enchanter the first camp was lost by the puller getting trapped in VS&amp;#8217;s domain.  The last camp with an excellent enchanter of mid 50 or better, failed when a pair of hands spawned as the puller brought in his prize.  Mez failed twice and he was dead before the heal spell finished casting.  Had he not had two hands and an extra pulled mob, I believe we could have held that room all night.  In RCY he was able to keep everything neatly parked.  In the hand room he was the first and admittedly the only one to die.  I believe he would not have died had we pulled the hands and killed them more slowly and separated the spawn times.<br><br>Med on the wall opposite of the door and things should be okay.  The room is small enough there is no safe place to med, but at the far wall you are furthest from the door and nothing aggroed us through that wall.<br><br>As in all things Everquest, if you want some of the good loot from the hands, you will need to camp that area for a long time.  It is a small area that is very active, and when you run screaming to the zone, you might impress a few novices by the train you will be pulling.<br><br>Trains:  When we wanted back into the RCY, it took us better than an hour, maybe two, to re-enter the court yard.  Just about when we had the path cleared, the rumblings of a train was heard and before that train was dealt with, the path was once more spawned.  Since that night there were camps all over the zone, Trains were coming in on top of each other.  Couple that with people not knowing to zone out left, oops LEFT, two or three trains and a host of players battling it out was impressive to say the least.  There was no concern as to whose dog or specter was whose, there was no concern if you healed your group or another person.  I would heal my group first then start searching to cast heals anywhere and everywhere.  We were all too stubborn to simply cede the entrance and simply zone and wait a couple of minutes to let all of KC calm back down.  But is was fun.  I hate to think of the prize loot that was left uncollected and simply rotted.  Even when the battle was over no one seemed interested in looting, perhaps fearful of taking someone else&amp;#8217;s loot.  So hardly anything was looted.<br><br>If you wish some idea of what it is like during a massive raid, come into KC when the basement, warlord room, and hand room all collapse within a few minutes of each other.  You will be surrounded by Ubers in their skivves numbering around thirty or so and a similar number of mob.  Have a fast computer and a good connection, the fireworks have just begun.<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue Jan  8 00:05:56 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>A simple cleric of Rodcet Nif on Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
