<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100546564962224></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100546564962224><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100546564962224>Today a most peculiar question</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100546564962224#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=46685><span id=Scholar>Laleldil</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>78 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Nov 11th 3:00 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.85]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Today I have decided to find a small quaint uninhabited cottage in the Southern Karanas and simply stop trying to increase my experiences with the deaths of others.&nbsp;&nbsp;Perhaps the foremost reasoning for this behavior, much to my friends in the Castle and others that anxiosly await my willingness to delve deep into Nagafen's Lair, is that the equipment that fate has so far endowed upon me is far too inadequate.  But also heavy in this decision was the incomprehensible notion that Nagafen is able to protect himself completely from those that are of fifty-three seasons or older.  As his life and death are such an extreme portion of my eventual epic quest, I need ponder the paths I must follow to attain this most potent artifact.  A third aspect of this decision has to do with my own guild.  Of late I have been alone to celebrate my victories and absent to enjoy the victories of my mates.  The Order of Green Knights is a young and small guild where ties are close and feelings run deep between us.  I miss them and go to stand behind them.<br><br>So today I set sail for Butcherblock, thence to Freeport itself.  After the beauty of the elven outpost of Firiona Vie and the far too short huts of the dwarves in Butcherblock, I found Freeport a relief and also a saddness.  It was a heart mixed with these feelings that I set off to the Bazzaare in the Eastern Commons.<br><br>I happened to over hear someone willing to part with a Charred Guardian Shield.  I asked the fellow how much platinum would he be willing to accept and recieved the cost as being four hundred platinum pieces.  Not having been greedy in the looting of the denizens of the castle, I am not a wealthy cleric, so offered him three hundred fifty platinum pieces.  With a laugh he suggested perhaps five hundred platinum pieces.  Obviously my bickering skills need some quick upgrading!  So I was left with the problem of whether to spend over half of my life savings for a shield or go without.<br><br>At that moment I heard a plaintive whisper asking if I would ressurect his/her fallen companion.  Naturally that now took precedence over all else, so as I walked the tunnel between Eastern Commons and Northern Ro, I decided to splurge and buy the shield if he were willing to take my four hundred platinum pieces.  I urged him to be patient and directly after this resurection I would gate to the bank and meet back with him in the tunnel.<br><br>Finding the corpse was pleasantly easy in the drifting sands near the camp the Dervs had erected.  However ressurecting him proved quite challenging!  Asking good Rodcet Nif to bring forth poor creature, all seemed well but nothing happened!  Another attempt failed as did several more attempts!  In a quandary I beseeched the Masters of the Game and was happily surprised by his very promptness!  He bid me cast again, yet that too failed in the attempt!  He then summoned his powers and cast, proclaiming that it worked.  Alas it did not!  He bid me to tell the lost soul to camp and return, again the spell was cast yet too soon the special vision the lost soul got faded too quickly and that too failed, though of course the Master had left for another missive thinking all was once more well.  I offered again my limited abilities and failed.  So bid the sould to camp yet once more and stand poised in utmost vigilance should his vision appear.  Thankfully that seemed to solve this most perplexing riddle.<br><br>I then proceeded to bank and tunnel and purchased the fine shield and was so very grateful that merchant was so patient.  I was pleased to have given him the four hundred, simply because he was so very kind.<br><br>I purchased a port to Northern Karanas and found some guard hiding in the far northeastern corner.  Querying him I found him to less then honorable so, well, er, took his helm and, ah, unfortunately his head was yet within it.<br><br>I swam to the bridge, hoping to rinse the stench of his blood, perhaps in my aged condition forgetting the flesh yet in my pack.  When I happened to enter Southern Karanas I ventured amidst the undead in search of some fellow named Grimroot.  He was, as usual, absent his post, so I settled at the bank of the river and caught fresh fish and attemted to construct fish rolls.  Alas I am such a terrible chef, I have much trouble making a rat sanwich, which even the youngest of bakers learn at youth.<br><br>Running out of worms to bait my hook, I figured to see if Grim-dude was yet about his post.  Instead of Ol'Grim I saw a dwarven cleric from the Forever Exiled guild slaying much undead.  I saw he was having little trouble and seemed not interested in the possible loot of the fallen, so I asked him were he awaiting Grim's return?  He laughed, that trait so enjoyable about dwarves, "Do you think I am here to kill skeletons?"<br><br>Admittedly that had crossed my mind for when I was younger I came at times to try and rid the foul stench of death from the land, though I had much more troubles with success then.  But when he had again slain a beligerant skeleton, he agreed he was wanting to have a special word with Ol' Grim.<br><br>Naturally, I made began preparations to camp and rest.  However just before I closed my eyes, I got the most peculiar question:<br><br>"Are you going to KS me?"<br><br>I was so stunned I froze and could not open my eyes!<br><br>First Sir, I am a Green Knight.  That should tell you the answer to your question.  Honor between mates and others is our highest priority.  I honor your attempts as much or more than I wish to be honored in mine.  I could not think to Kill Steal.<br><br>Second Sir, I am Laleldil.  I must be true to myself above all others.  Were you unfortunately slain in your attempts and I successful to bring the foul to his death.  I would sooner ressurrect you and bid you loot your victory before I would deign touch the corpse you were caming.<br><br>Third Sir, I am sorry you have happened upon such people that you seemed to expect such vile treatment.  I hope someday to be at your side when that happens again.  I will stand beside you.<br><br>I wish you luck Sir and pleasant hunting.<br><br>For others: should you walk with a Green Knight you walk with one that holds honor most dear.<br>&nbsp;<br>A simple cleric of Rodcet Nif on Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
