<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100538905237680></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100538905237680><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100538905237680>To visit a Dragon</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100538905237680#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=46685><span id=Scholar>Laleldil</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>78 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Nov 10th 5:44 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.85]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I am now, aye currently, exactly half way through my 49th season.&nbsp;&nbsp;I have battled, hehe, such as a not battle cleric might, across the dreadlands and even into Karnor's castle itself.  I have faced death and lived and I have faced life and died.  I have seen great ones felled and seen young ones trumpting joy of victory.  I?  I am a cleric, sworn to heal for Rodcet Nif, sworn to honorability through the Order of Green Knights.  I have experienced much, yet seem to forever find I have experienced nothing.  Upon my back still rests the tattered remains of my bearskin cloak and I have never yet seen the Planes of any kind, nor laid eyes upon a mighty dragon.<br><br>Yet agian I opened my eyes just within the Castle, where I began to quickly prepare for the day's events to unfold, summoning food and drink as was my want at the start of every day.  No longer surprised, I discovered myself alone except for the terrible creatures of the Castle.  Yet as frequently happens others came into the castle and a small group was beginning to form.  Though not an impressive grouping, we were just beginning to assault the castle and its inhabitants.<br><br>Eerily a voice whispered to me, asking if I would be willing to delve deep within Nagafen's Lair and lay the beast to rest.  Since I had not as yet gotten too deeply involved within the group nor was the group in direct danger with my leaving, I gave notice to the group that I was indeed going to join a raid against the fell dragon.  Attempts to locate a replacement cleric went unsuccessful and it soon became apparent that others in the group were also being invited to join the foray to the depths of the Lair.  Thus, as this young group began to disperse, I was soon ported to Lavastorm's peculiar environs and entered my first experience with a dragon.<br><br>Alas all was not going so well right from the start, since I had died by a great host of creatures pulled from the interiors of the castle.  Even as the mists around me swirled and opened in the port, the ressurection effects and absence of mana was painful to experience.  Seemingly my accompanying group members were deaf to my pleas for patience, because they soon bounded over crevice and rise.  It seemed only the dire warning that my bind point was in Firona Vie gave them slight pause.  Every attempt to sit and concentrate to increase my magikcal potential was interrupt by wandering foes.  Once more near death, I literally begged them to keep the beasts from sending me back to a far away continent, thus seperating me from my scant few belongings.  It was almost with grim humor and unexpected pleasure that I told them when asked to dispell magically the charm upon one of their friends that I had still no mana and thus no way to abet them in thier problem.<br><br>Be that as it may, the group eventually, a few moments, later deigned to appease my whimperings of fear and agony by returning to the druid ring and allowing me the blissful influx of magiks and health.<br><br>Upon my sitting and meditating the events unfolding and about to unfold, more valiant heroes and heroines began to assemble to slay the dragon.  I, admittedly ill prepared in all ways for this adventure, informed those about me, including the Master Leader of my utter lack of experience and knowledge, gathered courage from those about me.  Shocked is a light description of how I felt when I petitioned the very etheral mists of the zone as to the clerics in Lavastorm.  There were but three clerics in the zone, a Vicar of some note, whispering he had yet to experience an assault on Nagafen, and a cleric of forty three seasons.  Though quite unnerved to be, at present the second highest cleric attending such an event, I took what comfort I could as others explained they had partaken many, many times in Nagafen's demise.  As I settled in my bear skin cape (wonder if I will ever set it aside, though I do not feel I will ever set this garment upon another's back) I listened to the reports that an invasion group was nearly complete in the clearing of foes up to the fire giants.  You, unless you are a weak-armed cleric with little skill or experience, will never know the joy that flooded my very being when the petition to the mists revealed that there were now about a half dozen clerics amidst us, one having attained the most senior level of knowledge and carried the lure of every cleric, the epic weapon.<br><br>The rush to the entrance to the Lair, after the groups were formed merely for entry and not the assault on the dragon, was more of a mad scramble and seemed quite chaotic.  Admittedly I have nothing upon which to judge the unfolding events since this was my first such foray into the Lair. My only previous entrance into the Lair was quite by accident while I was searching for the Temple of Ro when questing for my gauntlet.<br><br>Things seemed to run steadily down hill from my zoning into the Lair.  Beset by gnolls (?) at the entrance, though easily defeated with little or no damage, my ignorance blossomed as I soon found myself lost remembering only a lava edge and a room just beyond with a ramp upwards.  I could sense my group mates distress and I tried to heal them, yet they were too far away for my magiks to reach.  My frightened advance and climbing the ramp seemed to bring me no closer, and the sounds of battle diminished.  I raced back down, jumped actually, and closed my eyes and hoped I entered the correct passage before me.  I found the lava edge and a quick turn of the corner gave me the pleasure to find my accompanying group.  Alas I had a Lava Crawler (?) nibbling on my bottom and they were quite busy with some fell spiders.  Though I managed to land a heal on my group leader, all further spells were interuptted and I soon lying in the dirt bleeding from foul wounds as the crawler took his last bite from my carcus.<br><br>So quiet and serene the land of Lavastorm seems after that surprising introduction into the Lair.  Alas my meager possessions resided somewhere within those vile passageways and I was naked at the druid ring.  Further to lay the heart heavy was that I was not alone!  Several of the Dragon Assault party was with me in their less then impressive attire.  However I was not left long to contemplate the situation, ere I was again summoned to my corpse.  Joyfully I looted my now more familiar state and proceeded to contemplate the events as the mana began to fill once more this fragile body.<br><br>As more and more corpses began to be dragged into the area we were in, which was the room with the ramp I had once previously ascended in hopes of finding my group, I kept busy healing the stricken and resting as my own health slowly returned.  Apparantly the area was being hunted by a small group and our sudden arrival of stricken and healthy gave immediate confusion.  With a few Dragon Party members in poor health, we, much to our dismay, felt forced to slay any and all intruding enemies, much to the previous hunters dismay and grief.  Eventually enough were ressurected and healed that we could, with heartfelt apology to the hunters, move our motely group up the ramp and thus towards our upcomming fate.<br><br>Actually I should mention that we were not all that bad an assembly.  Though admittedly I was again unnerved as the leader of my group advanced to a fire giant and died even though I was casting Superior Heal immediately upon his first wound!  He and I were equally stunned.  He apparently believing I was a lax cleric and I have never experienced one of my charges dying in the duration of a superior heal cast!  And if it had landed it was all too apparent that it would have been an exercise in futility!<br><br>Praise Rodcet Nif he learned extremely fast not to have the whole and entire attention of a Fire Giant!<br><br>Otherwise it was quite comforting actually in our advance through the giants.  Even though the pullers frequently were slain, we managed to quickly dispense our justice on the giants even when there came three to interfere with our goal.<br><br>Almost too soon, though my short little dip in lava was terribly frightening, we were all hale and hearty at the entrance to the dragon's lair itself.  There is a peculiar feel when one views for the first time the stone entrance carved into the resemblance of a dragon's mouth open with sharp stalagtites and stalactites for the most foul fangs warning of impending peril.<br><br>Immediately new groups were assembled and orders given to begin the buffing.  Odd and peculiar buffs were cast in all directions!  See Invisible? Much to my education these seldom unused and seemingly wasted buffs were as much protection and more valuable than the group magical resistence and health buffs that they defended.  Nagafen could and would begin to remove any magical defenses we had upon us, so the important ones were deeply covered in great layers of 'useless' protections and spells.  As group after group became covered in various magiks they were asked to bed and relax so as not to allow the 'buffs' to slowly deplete.<br><br>When my group was bedded, so to speak, we entered a dreamland where disembodied spirits talked.  Aye!  I was one of the disembodied!  Jesting and light heartedness and frequent assurances that all was at hand, I listened quietly to the chatter and awaited the instructions the Master Leader was about to speak.<br><br>Though not his exact words, this is my best remembrance and interpretations:<br><br>"We are a group of thirty bent on the destruction of the foul dragon Nagafen.  Certain items are reserved for certain others, though some things will be available to all with a need before greed basis.  These are the groups that will be formed...."<br><br>I heard my name listed in the second group, and was heartened that my leader was someone I had grown to appreciate in the short time of this adventure.<br><br>"The actual assault will begin with group one and upon my command all other groups will immediately assault and finish slaying the fell dragon."<br><br>Uhm, sounded simple enough.  Basically wait for a 'go' then 'go' in and begin healing my warrior.<br><br>Unfortunately between times of my leaving the realm of the disembodied to the reoccurence of mind and body, somehow the groups were redivided into six equal groups of five, and the warrior I anticipated to heal was replaced with another.  Though unnerved by this rapidly changing chain of events, I remember Maduber as a valiant and exceptional fighter of some great merit.  It was simply then just a change from one fighter to another.<br><br>It began then.<br><br>Group one charged up the ramp and disappeared.  Suddenly the call came for all to invade Nagafen's domain.  I too, seemingly following instructions, went up the ramp, found steps and a portal into a large area.  Near the back side of the area that was Nagafen's nest, a great battle was being fought.  Almost immediately Maduber was in the midst of battle and taking wounds with greivice rapidity.  Unaware, not that it matters, that I was also being ripped assunder by the dragon's foul roars.  Hardly had the first spell landed to heal Maduber when was I knocked senseless then passed into death at the center of Nagafen's nest!<br><br>I 'respawned', so to speak, quickly memorized Superior Healing and raced back to the dragon's lair.  While traveling up the steps I encountered many racing in terror down the steps.  Imagine my shock to see Nagafen still a full quarter alive and heeding his summons to join him as dinner!<br><br>Again I quickly memmed Superior Heal and also too Celestial Healing, and raced again to attempt to target any one to heal.  Between being feared and summoned I died several more times.  Realizing the futility of trying to heal anyone, I changed tactics to try and assault the dragon directly.  Memorizing an attack spell of some note, at least for a cleric, I raced up to the dragon, hearing the warning given casters repeated between my dense ears to be within melee range for a spell to land successfully, and stood directly under the dragon and began to cast my spell.<br><br>Luckily for a moment the dragon ignored me.  Unluckily the spell was resisted.  Further ill luck came as the dragon simple swated me three times and left me dead again at his feet.  My instruction on dying and futility ended sometime after my seventh death, when I simply quit counting death as significant.  Already my  forty-ninth season was history as well as my intentions to aide somehow in its death without reorganizations.<br><br>It did not happen.<br><br>What strength a warrior naked and unarmed against such a foe?  Quickly recovering his foul health, even the magiks of the casters were easily overcome.  My heart and hopes sank as the last death was by a dragon now nearly fully healed and my meager possessions lay somewhere buried in the pile of corpses that the laughing dragon reigned over.<br><br>Lamentations and accusations abounded, much to my dismay.  Surely those of experience were aware that a hastily assembled group of the inexperienced could lead to a raid of less then stellar success.  Perhaps they were correct in some of their accusations and criticisms.  One thing I do know that they, with their sharp tongues, were saying was not true.  If assaulting the dragon and forcing it back into the corner to be slain was good, then clerics, at least to heal the fighters, must too enter the lair.  The pretense of incredulity as to my entering the lair utterly floored me.  How did they expect me to heal them when they were out of range?<br><br>There was naught to do of course but to begin the sombering ritual of gathering the dead from the steps and finally the incredibly brave rogue (15 seasons old?) actually sneaking into the blodied lair itself to pull the multitude of corpses from the heap.  Wadl you were heroic and most amazing!<br><br>Gratefully I accepted the ressurections by the most high priest and her epic weapon.  As I meditated and healed others, I would soon once more be ressurected and left with no mana and weak.  Other than Wadl the Amazing Rogue and one other Vhenlador (?) there simply was not much use for healing or clarity as the bodies began to pile up around us.<br><br>Although there was talk, and the pretty and powerful Enchantress eager to take revenge, it was also a time when others felt it was time to go their way and find other things to do.  Unfortunately enough were leaving and there were few takers on the mists to join us so the final tally was Nagafen bunches Dragon Party zero.<br><br>Thus was, and so far is my full introduction to the Lair of Nagafen.  Though I had to decline an invitation to raid Vox's lair the next evening, it was not from fear of dying, I have done that quite a bit actually now.  Nor was it from any fear to go anywhere with the leaders of this raid.  We all learn, sometimes painfully, with every misstep.  I would gladly follow this particular guild into a fight.  Hopefully they will invite this simple cleric on another raid when they have it early in the day as I sadly work like a vampire in the dark of night.<br><br>To those I have met on this raid I thank you, for instruction on how to live and how to die.<br><br>Hehe I also now how Tynnkny came so soon to battle, unless I am mistaken, of course.  A dead corpse from a death caused by a mob, not a duel as that only last ten minutes I heard, can act in what I would describe as a death bind.  In the worst case emergency ressurecting that corpse might prove the only way to bring oneself so quickly to battle as a warrior.  Receiving a complete heal and scooping up weapon, though admittedly not the prettiest, especially as being a troll, or most effective, fighting without armor, does give a warrior something to fight with anyway.<br><br>Postscript to whom it may concern:  I have apparently only lost a slight bit of memories, apparently from over eagerly looting a corpse.  So I am once more, halfway... er nearly halfway... through the 49th season of experience.<br>&nbsp;<br>A simple cleric of Rodcet Nif on Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
