	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Nov 10th 3:35 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.71]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>First I am surprised that this journal as gotten rated (wow) and that there are a lot of hits!<br><br>At times a war:<br><br>I had just entered my forty fourth season of service to the god Rodcet Nif.&nbsp;&nbsp;I happened to over hear that Nif, in his wisdom and desire to ever prove his clerics, has offered a special spell to his young wards, Celestial Healing.  The challenge he offered me while I fought for the cause in the sandy and often blizzard realm of the Dreadlands about Karnor's Castle was to locate and defeat an Ancient Shardwurm and loot the spell he had given it to carry.  Thus I had inadvertantly, at least on my part, managed to find myself in the following predicament.<br><br>I hunkered down deeper into the slight warmth that the deep snow of the strange yet beautiful area about the dark wurm hole called Greater Divide.  How could I have ever happened to be clutching my ragged bearskin cloak and staring at the formidable line of Giant Spearmen?  Surely this was all a mistake!<br><br>I had been deep within the wurm hole, struggling mightily to heal and protect two over eager wurm slayers of admittedly great skill and even greater generousity.  Many wurms were struck down and looted, yet none were the wurm I needed that carried the gift of Rodcet Nif that I craved.  At times we were heavily besieged on all sides as those great brutes fought to evict us from their lair.  Oft times it was slightly slower with just two or three attacking the Fair Enchantress and her friend.  Never was there a moment when we were left in peace and the mana presense was critically low at nearly every moment.<br><br>Busy I was, yet never too busy not to hear a call of need.  At first I thought it was the call of a friend and brother in our guild, the Order of Green Knights, yet later I learned such was not the case.  I responded to the call and heard a calm voice suggesting perhaps I would like to aide another's quest.  Unfortunately I seem to be ever eager to adventure and so I heartily agreed to make my way up the river and thus to meet in front of the Dwarven Town there that is hidden behind the mists and sprays of a great water fall that creates the river at its foot.  Time was passing fast, and the other two members of the wurm group was not slowing down in the least, so eventually I had to beg them to allow me to leave.  The air was filled with the rumors of war.  I could not fanthom why, was there not enough evil in the world that war was ever to be engaged?<br><br>Frazzled from my just ended fruitless wurm adventure, I was stunned by the sight that greeted me.  Aye the sun was shining brightly, that enough of a surprise from being in the darkened depths of the lair.  But to my utter surprise there was a great multitude of people assembled with great arms and even greater magiks!  I was in complete awe as I gazed about me in an area I often found near deserted.  Priests of near every god of great level was joined with the most vile Iskars, Trolls, and Dark Elves!  Aye the Shamans, Warriors, Wizards and, yes, people of all races and classes were seeming to be joining forces!  And all of them seemed very learned and aged, thus once more teaching me the humility of being one so young in his god's sevice.<br><br>The one that called me from the depths of the wurm cavern greeted me and asked if I would set awhile as the forces began to assemble in groups.  I tried to count the assembled, yet there were far too many for me to count.  This list I gathered of just the wizards, magicans,and other summoners of instant death, was at least twenty or more names of notables that were every one more senior and experienced than I.  These were perhaps the fewest in number!<br><br>Right behind me began to assemble a group that both inspired me and filled me with great fear.  It was the ressurection group headed by a godlike cleric of great report skill and he carried a weapon of great magiks.  Reportedly he could raise the dead and bring back all remembrances and skills!  Flanking him were two fearsome rogues of great experience and I can not now recall who else attended to this Supreme Healer, I was simply to filled with awe and a great fear as I contemplated with my lack of knowledge what possible event might be occurring that a group like this was summoned to perform resurrecting of the fallen!<br><br>Lists were ever being compiled, and I was sore afraid to add my name to the list of clerics.  Thankfully, Rodcet Nif be praised, clerics were the first asked to join the gathering by list.  I was assigned to an Eastern Battalion.  Battalion?  Yes, the Master Leader was forming not groups as I have only experienced, he was literally forming armies!  Dutifully I ventured to the site of the Eastern Battalion assemply point, there met already a multitude of many all mightier than I. It appeared, though clerics were first assembled by list, much planning had already occurred and many already knew before hand into which Battalion they would be engaged in.  Perhaps the lists being compiled by the Master Leader was more to ease the tremulous that joined his cause or perhaps just to make sure all unexpected participants were charted and assigned, such as I was.<br><br>I knelt humbly by a great white bear and asked what was going on.  (Why not ask a bear?  Seemed far less threatening then the skeletons, Iskars, Ogres, Trolls, and others who just by the glint of their weapons or sparkling of their Magiks caused my heart to beat rapidly and my knees to tremble to the verge of collapse!)  To my astonishment the bear began to speak in soft dulcimer tones explaining he was a shaman who was giving service to the Master Leader Tynkny (spelling is off I know) who was completing a great quest, this last part was known as the tenth ring.<br><br>It seemed that when Tyknny (sounded like Tiny)gave something to the Dwarves of Coldain and/or something verbal, the leader of the dwarves would accept his offer of alliance to defend the dwarven outpost.  This was no small event.  Instead it was and incredible and awesome enough event that the snows, hills and even the carvern and the wurms took note of!  Nothing and no one was going to interfere in the upcomming event.  No wurm would spawn and attack anyone, even the wolves that frequented the area would slink off to hide will the terrifying event took place.  Were it not for the tone of his voice and his calm demeanor I too would have fled the area, what possible event would be so dire and terrifying that even the wolves would tuck tail and hide until all was returned to order?<br><br>"We are about to engage in a war.  It is quite simple really," the great bear spoke as he examined his mighty clawed paw leisurely.  "We will either succeed in defending this small simple minded folk or die."  I stared at him, his great maul curled in a smile and eyes glittering in anticipation of the kill!  I surely swooned in fear for I remember not much else, save a wild race to a small valley and the orders to defend such valley from giants soon to appear.<br><br>Unfortunely I do remember one utterly mystifying thing (for I know no other term that would detail this strange...er.... thing!)  I was chosen my the Eastern Battalion Leader to lead a group of five others!  Forgive me Nif for my so tremulous quivering, yes I thank you deeply that the great bear was also of the group!  Though I remember not his name it sort of remined me of something like apignew but that is very far off and that is certain.  Then there was the sudden race through the deep snow to the valley as directed and the admonishment still ringing in my ears to never, at any time, advance towards the Giant Spearmen as they would summon you and with great alarcity impale you to a most indignant death!<br><br>Which brings me once more to my huddled form in the old bear skin cape deep in a bank of snow, taking what comfort I could take from the sight of the great bear comfortably gazing at the line of Giant Spearmen.  Around me swirled rumors even more confusing then the oft swirling gusts of snow.  "Are we in the right valley?"  "Aye the giants will be attacking from the spearmen's left flank coming up this valley."  The sound of battle came easily through the frigid cold!  "All ASSIST ME ON ..." the sound of the Master Leader rang through out the zone.  "Heal Tynnkny!"  "Attacking ..."  "All attack ..." "WE are being flanked to the right, swing right!"  "... down, ressurect him!"  I trembled as the words, excited by war, yet seemed so controlled and experience, came to my ears.  And yet I could only wait, stare with the bear at the yet unmoving line of Spearmen, and dread the fear welling in my belly.<br><br>"Eastern Battalion assist to your right!"  Those words rang in my ears, stunning me to sudden shock!  I leapt up and saw the great bear and our whole battalion already scrambling up the sides of the valley, some already disappearing as they dropped over the top!  I too raced, though admittedly more to just be with someone far away from the territying yet unmoving line of the great enemy, then in great anticipation of battle.  Yet, too, I had given my word, thus a solemn unbreakable vow to a person I am sure does not know I even exist.  I let duty, the fact that I am, though young and unworthy, a healer of Rodcet Nif, and my sudden friendship with this great bear take me over the hill and into a swirling cyclone of events that engulfed me.<br><br>I had thought the Eastern Battalion had advanced apparently much farther than we had!  For immediately I recognized we were just south of Coldain!  The Middle Army was in a terrific contest with many dead and dying littering the once glittering pure white of the Great Divide with blood and corpses of fallen heroes and hewn giants!  The beast beside me roared in pleasure and raced down the slippery slope and launched his great bulk into the very midst of the advancing line of giants that treatened to break around the Middle Battalion's flank!  With the drunkedness of war, I too raced to battle that which assaulted the hosts of my Master Leader.<br><br>(Sure wish I could remember that bear's name, for Tynnkny would be amazed at his fearlessness and bravory!)  Appigneu ?  not correct I know.<br><br>The great bear received a might blow that sent his blood and fur to add further to the ruined picturesqueness of the wonderous area.  I immediately began to summon health for him, casting the mightiest of heals of short spell duration.  Yet Superior healing seemed hardly to dent the terrific damage done to my newest of friends!  Again and again I cast the healing spells, yet the etheral mists of the zone seemed to deny me the ability to heal any of my quickly ailing group!  Futilely I stepped closer, the bear's bulk filling my vision as he still, though now half alive, rose on his hind feet and took massive bites of giant flesh and spit them to the ground.  Fully, terrifyingly, twenty or thirty seconds after I cast my first heal spell, I saw a slight rise in the bear's health.<br><br>Then I was driven, still standing, feet first into the frozen snow and ground, crumbling instantly when the giant brought his great fist down on my head!  Perhaps it took more than one blow, yet the swirling confusion of the zone and the terribly ther mists, most assuredly had frozen me at the giants feet and thus to my sudden painful death.<br><br>By the time I had awakened at the bind point just inside Coldain, I was already being revived by the godlike cleric!  Instantly I was standing at my corpse, though with little health, very tired, and no mana with which to heal.  I immediately looted the corpse at my feet and felt the sudden fresh breeze fill my mind and yet other magiks from the attending enchanter!  Wisdom filled my mind, though I would need a second to rest to accept the influx of mana from the mists.<br><br>With just a heals worth of mana I sluggishly went to find my group of which only the great bear and another.  As I approached the littered area of corpses and battle, again the etheral mists of the zone began to dull my senses.  Though I saw not my great friend, I head his call from the original valley we were to defend!  I immediately tried to race to his aid, yet came immediately upon yet another great contest!  Several giants were far too close to the town!  I immediately began to heal, and thus apparently, again sealed my fate of death.  The last I saw as I crumpled into the snow was the giant stepping over me and another giant fallin like a great tree, felled by our mighty forces!<br><br>Though the etheral mists of the zone was greatly impeding me, I managed several times to enter the great war, once even to attain the battle in our valley and finding comfort that the great bear had taken over leadership of the group and had gathered most of my former members and another ungrouped participant of this terrible great war.<br><br>I can not now tell you whether we managed to defeat the enemy in or valley or if indeed they managed to flank us.  For as the etheral mists hindered me, giants seemed every where, storming down slopes determined to slay those oddly indifferent ungrateful dwarves!  Soon I was back at the entrance to Coldain, advancing drunkedly with fatigue and battling a mist that threatened to obliterate me utterly from the zone.<br><br>I saw it then.<br><br>It was in essense the last of the great battles.  The wave of the giants, think it was called the third wave, was comprised of their most elite and highest ranking giants.  Reputed to have been all of sixty seasons, though I could not confirm that rumor.  Not only were there few of them left standing to assail the dwarves, Tyknny was swinging his weapon standing toe to toe with the greatest of all giants.  Corpses seemed to be tripping friend and foe alike at every movement.  Many valiant heroes and and heroiness contested the advancing giants dressed as on the day of their birth, taking just the moment to heft great sword or spell ere returning to Tynnkny's aide.<br><br>Despite the infernal ehteral mists that sorely treated me, I saw my greatest of heroes, being bashed and slashed for great damage.  My last successful targeting and casting was at that great hulk of Troll flesh. Perhaps ogre? Tis hard at times to discern the difference without looking at the purple eyes and hooked beak of a nose!  The spell of mine or another, though I heard confirmation through the mists that Tynnky ws completely healed, landed solidly and gave me great joy.  Alas the mists refused to lessen their assault on my person, and I could do more but futilely attempt to heal who Tynnkny was calling someone to heal.  Unfortunately I saw Tyknny fall in death, yet was shocked to see him come running near naked from the town, stoop and retrieve just his weapon and again assail that terrible giant!  The giant was soon felled and a great shout of victory was heard through out the zone!  Apparently, though there were yet a couple giants left standing, the war, and its goals were seemingly complete.  'Course it helped, I presume, as the giants that were left standing were suddenly overwhelmed in great forces and sent rapidly to the blood soaked tundra.<br><br>I could barely sit there, the excitement and joy, no perhaps better called elation, ran so deep and wide throughout the area.  Congrateulations flew through the air and continued impressively even when those wolves, dwarves, and wurms re-entered the Greater Divide.  (Seemed quite a rude shock when the most ungrateful of dwarves actually attacked one of the gallant that had just successfully saved their hovel from being swept from the face of Norrathe!)  Be that as it may, there were yet more rejoicing and congratulations as items looted found new owners.  Laughter and shouts filled the area.<br><br>My quiet voice for a sow went unheeded, so I just shrugged my shoulders, again huddled into the warmth of my comforting robe, and began the short walk to the Eastern Wastelands and the Dreadlands that summoned me to regain the level lost.  I guess in my excited state I was too eager to accept or wait for a ressurection, accepting the full mana as a greater gift then the memories of the past.<br><br>Though I learned I was not a good enough cleric to battle giants and etheral mists of a zone in battle, I was happy and joyous in heart and spirit.  To that great warrior, I owe many thanks.  To that great bear I owe much comfort and beg the day comes when I might again be at his side, more secure in my abilities to heal.  To the others that attended that great war, you have instructed me in ways not imagined previously, and I thank you everyone.  But mostly I wish to thank whomever it was that first whispered to me of their desire for me to partake of the event and Rodcet Nif for inviting me to be where I was when I was.  Were it not for that unknown individul and my quest to obtain the elusive spell, I would not have been able to partake in the most exciting adventure in my 44 ... er 43 .. hehehe ... seasons!<br>&nbsp;<br>A simple cleric of Rodcet Nif on Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
