<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100511381051967></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100511381051967><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100511381051967>Pictures fo r that Tale</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100511381051967#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=46685><span id=Scholar>Laleldil</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>78 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Nov 7th 1:16 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.80]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>In another journal one asked how to view the pictures he took as he wished to tell an illustrated tale.&nbsp;&nbsp;To that end I will put a more detailed filled description as to how I manage the pictures.<br><br>First of all you are going to take some great pictures!  That gorgeous enchantress that just gave you a round of crack and even now is casting yet another spectacular spell would be the perfect subject.  Or is it that elephant lying dead at the very top of a tree in Southern Karana the picture you want?  Or perhaps you are providing a detailed description of a dungeon for your guild mates and want them to actually see the turns and rooms before they are confronted with monsters of all kinds.  Pictures of course can clear things up or make them murky depending in your skill and patience.<br><br>Before you take that picture though think a few seconds on why you want the picture and to what you hope to use it!  Is it a new found friend you wish to immortalize in living, er dead, color?  Please leave the display PC names on.  Make sure the name tag is nicely contrasted and legible.  Should you rather tell a tale in role play then most likely you would not like the confusion of so many overlapping names 'dirtying' the picture.  Surely Sir Galahad never rode into battle with his name tag joining a host of other name tags!  If you are making a pictorial sequence for others to follow, try to put your curser pointing at the key part you wish them to notice.  But most of all have fun and snap frequently.  Quick punching the - key can give something interesting, I'll explain later.<br><br>Using the F10 key changes your screen I believe from a windowed format, to a windowed format with clear frames, and then a full screen picture without anything else on the screen. A third F10 will bring you back to the original screen.  What you see picture-wise is the same content in all three modes with just the size of the picture varying.  The windowed picture has just as much view area as the full screen only smaller, like looking at a 5x7 or an 8x10 of the same picture.<br><br>Using F9 alters the angle from which the picture on the screen is viewed.  It is a camera-like function.  Perhaps as you are trying to explain the pathing of a mob or which entrance to go through, the overhead view would explain it best. In Karnor's castle the first two guardians run to the center of the path, then come down the center to attack you the intruder.  On over head view can be used with lines drawn in towards the center and then down the hall.  By doing this with several diferent monsters you will notice how they move to get friends just before they come for you.  By attacking the right one on the right side, will it still run to your left and then to you? Uhm, a picture can help.<br><br><br>You have now taken your pictures:  Where are they?<br>Answer: In your Everquest directory.  If you did the normal install, probably, if I am not mistaken, Verant thought it would be nice to put Everquest in your Program folder on the main root of your C drive.  For those of you who have decided to put the game in a games folder, like I did, then Everquest is in that folder.<br><br>Question: Where and what are they?<br>Answer: Eq0000.bmp is the first picture you took.  The next one is eq0001 and so on.  Now I am not a computer whiz, so I won't even try to explain what a bmp file is other than it is apparently one of the simplest of graphics files that most all programs can display, from your paint program in windows accessories to the most complex of programs.  It is huge.<br><br>Question: How do I view this picture?<br>Answer: By finding the file with windows explorer, most likely you can preview it right in explorer.  You can also double click the file name and your default image viewer for bmp's will open the picture.<br><br>Question: Now what?<br>Answer: Now you have to decide what you are intending to do and how many pictures you are going to be taking.<br><br>I, personally, created a screenshot folder in everquest.  Inside screenshot I created a temp folder.  Since I use PaintshopPro5, though I imagine most all image programs like imagefolio, PhotSuite, etc have similar mechanics, I will go through the process I use.  P5 has a convert sub program under file tab.  By setting the destination folder to temp, I can select all the bmp from eq0000 to the last eq00xx and simply click convert.  Whala! eq0000.jpd in temp folder and eq0000.bmp in everquest folder.  CAREFULLY delete eq0000.bmp, you might check eq0000.jpg first but it should be okay.<br><br>Now you still got some things to do!  Rename these files!  Your next screenshot will be eq0000.bmp!  You now already have a eq0000.jpg!  Make yet more folders!  I made folders for various zones like SKarana, EKarana, HighholdP, etc.  'Guildmates' is another good name and 'maps'.  Name your new eq0000.jpg something informative.  skarana0000.jpg perhaps.  You can now save 10,000 pictures of skarana and all of them can have a different name, everyone of them right where you expect it to be (time wise).  Sneaking in at level 12? skarana0000 might be the first sight you saw.  Now a fearless uber warrior skarana1223.jpg will be much lower in the list.<br><br>Break out and dust off your cdwriter!  If you become addicted to taking pictures you will want to start cleaning your C drive of the thousands of pictures you quickly accumulate!<br><br>Remember the previously mentioned quick punches of screenshot key I mentioned earlier?  Lets look at that for a second or so.  You are witnessing a a terrific battle and not really doing all that much yourself.  I am a cleric so have some seconds at times to do this.  Quick go put pc names off, quick go to full screen adjust view, sit, jump up, look higher, sit again, and start punching key.  Whew!  Fight was won and you took 25 pictures.<br><br>Now outside of Eq.  I still use P5.  I convert as normal.  Use the program my friend created to automatically sequencially rename pictures.  Now we have fight0000.jpg to fight0024.jpg.  Open P5's animation program.  Insert pictures in sequence and create animated gif!  Ah! a short home movie of the fight in living color!<br><br>If I figure out how to give access to a program from my website I will put a flag here to send you there should you want a sequencing naming program.  Since it was a modification of another program he wrote to move files and such it is slightly confusing, but the part I use is exceptionally easy.<br><br>Though windy, I hope this helps all the aspiring journalists to get their pictures!  Display them proudly, not everyone has gotten where you have been and we eagerly await your illustrated tales of glory.<br><br>Laleldil Tremulous &lt;Order of Green Knights&gt;<br>49 Cleric in Rodcef's service<br>Tholuxe Paells server<br>&nbsp;<br>A simple cleric of Rodcet Nif on Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
