<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100486075677671></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100486075677671><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100486075677671>A Tale</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100486075677671#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=46685><span id=Scholar>Laleldil</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>78 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Nov 4th 2:59 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.75]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>A Tale<br><br>I had decided to once more cross Kithichor Forest, pass through Highhold Pass, harvest a few pieces of spider silk, then continue on to Qeynos and turn in the quantity of bone chips I had gathered over the last several seasons.&nbsp;&nbsp;I was admittedly quite proud of the fact that I had over 200 bone chips to give to Lashon, or whatever his name was.  With luck the Temple of Life would hold me even higher within their favor and perhaps even give me a more noble quest to perform.  I paused in the Pass to again look into the ever continuing struggle underneath the Keep.  True to form, young folk of Norath had again banded together and valiantly fought to stop yet another rush of vermin that threatened the security of the Keep.  I watched from the top of the stairs, occasionally casting the spells I had come to accept as my greatest of gifts the Temple had bestowed upon me.  As the furious pace slowed and all seemed secure for the moment, I continued by own travels and headed out across Eastern Karana.<br><br>Actually travel had become somewhat easier as I had put a few more seasons behind me.  Being allowed the ability to set my own bind spots, something I have never yet been able to accurately understand,  gave me some advantages others were not so fortunate to have.  When I am overcome and need the gods to bring me back, I usually, if I remembered, had a much shorter travel to &#8216;loot my corpse&#8217;.  With this freedom I had ventured farther afield around Freeport, my adopted town, and Qeynos, the town I seemed to have originated from.  I, though obviously not bold and brave, hence the name that was given to me by the Temple, Tremulous, had traveled a few seasons across the mighty ocean wandering Butcherblock, Faydwer, and parts to the Karanas with a few hard fought seasons spent in Split Paw Lair.  I often thought of a cleric I had met in Qeynos and tried to emulate him in every way possible. I still warmed my innards to remember one fine beautiful morning outside Felwithe.<br><br>I had just gotten up from my rest and meditation when this most spectacularly beautiful High Elf lady asked if I could help her get her corpse.  Hehe, how could I refuse!  Summoning forth the magiks given me, I covered her in every form of safety I could give her.  Protection of the gods, more health from courage, and the symbol that was mine at the time.  Not stopping there, perhaps admittedly to impress her, I continued my casting buffing her against the perils of poison, disease, fire, cold, and even magik!  I gallantly stood up as she giggled nervously and offered to escort her to her corpse.  &#8220;Really, kind Sir, my corpse is just over the rise there.  I will be quite safe enough in your magiks and my invisibility!&#8221;  Suddenly she disappeared!  Though I heard her yet before me, &#8220;Perhaps now safe from you.&#8221;  Once more her laughter tinkled like silvery bells in my ears.  Yes, as I think about it now, perhaps she was correct.  She was beautiful!<br><br>But that was long ago and even her name is becoming cloudy from poor memory.  Eyllane?  My how terrible it feels to begin to forget the beauty we have seen.<br><br>Coming across Eastern Karana I managed to kill a small number of giant spiders of varying breeds.  As I neared the wooden bridge to Northern Karana, I happened upon a Crag Spider, perhaps noted as being one of the deadliest spiders of all Antonica.  Though not completely filled with the mana I could have had, I quickly smote the spider with magiks, then began to swing my Wraith Bone hammer as fast as I could swing it.  As unfortunately it seems to happen frequently, my magikal buffing began to drop of one by one.  Cold, fire, and magic buffs were of no loss, but I became scared when the poison buff also faded away.  Not to be out done, the last three buffs also decided to fade away, leaving me alone to face the spider with only my hammer and my small pool of mana.<br><br>The spider&#8217;s sharp talons cut into my skin frequently, then his evilly poisoned fangs bit into my arm and I felt the searing burn as the poison was pumped into my body!  I swung frantically at the dark head and merely glanced the chitinous surface.  Another talon stabbed into my thigh.  One that gave me the pleasure of hearing it cracking, making the spider scream its eery scream as my hammer bashed it into pieces!  Though, at first thought, close to the safety of the bridge that the spider could not cross, it became terrifyingly evident as the poison coursed through my body and weakened me, one of us, possibly both of us was going to die.  Savagely the battle raged for what seemed like hours and mere seconds.  Talon cutting deep as often as my hammer cracking the tough skin of the spider.  Green ichor from the spider mingled and blended with the bright red of my own freely flowing blood.  Panic and terror threatened to make my swings even weaker and more inaccurate as my health was dropping just as fast as the spider seemed to be flagging.  As the last of my magiks was again resisted by the spider, I knew my death had once more come to claim me.  I cried in frustration and gave one last mighty crushing blow with my hammer and the spider turned away!  Do I run to the bridge and safety?  No there was no safety there, the poison yet ran through my body and my death was already sealed.  Angrily I charged after that terrible menace, blow after blow not landing and crashing against the bright red bulb of evil.  Finally with one last screech of pain the spider crumbled in a heap.<br><br>I stood panting feeling the last of life leave my body.  I knelt and examined the corpse and found nothing of value.  The last I remembered was collapsing in the blood of our battle and coming to rest on the hard slick shell of the spider.<br><br>I entered into the town of Riverdale.  The streets were quaintly curved around tiny little cottages.  Strange how serene an area can be after the terrors of Kithicor Forest.  In a small open area between two such small cottages I observed an old dwarf overseeing the play of a pretty little elfin girl whose age was hard to tell.  After all, dwarves live several hundred years, elves even twice as long, and us humans hardly ever see a hundred, yet we all seem to age the same.  Would the young elfin Maiden be a hundred, thus far older than I and almost half as old as the dwarf that sat tending her?  I put her age as I could understand, she was about five, maybe six tops in human years.<br><br>The little maiden crawled up into the old dwarven lap and nestled against the chest of the old dwarf.<br><br>&#8220;Tell me a story.&#8221; Her voice sounded so sweetly as an elderly Elfin Matron came forth from the cottage behind them with a tankard of Dwarven Brew and a thin narrow class of Elven Wine.  &#8220;Please.&#8221;<br><br>&#8220;Bah!&#8221; the Dwarf groused, thought he twinkle in his eyes gave away his true feelings.<br><br>&#8216;One day very long ago, a young man was walking through the hills of Butcherblock, following a trail not often used.  Well he happened upon the main path just as a young elfin Maid, not too much older than you, came crashing out of the brambles and briars that lined the main path.  The young man quickly and gallantly came to the Maid&#8217;s rescue, casting a root to the orc that chased her, a heal to the Maid, then struck quickly and fiercely against the orc with both magik and might.  Well the battle ended almost before it began and the orc soon lay at the man's feet.&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;The two decided to travel a ways together for safety.&#8217; The dwarf gave a grunt of laughter, &#8216;not that the man needed any protection!&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;He began to lead down the somewhat narrow path with the pretty Elfin Maiden, almost as pretty as you, following closely behind.  Wouldn&#8217;t you know some orc would have jumped out of the trees along the path and gave the Maid a mean and vicious blow with his rusty sword.  As he rapidly turned to attack he saw the orc&#8217;s arm uplifted and poised to come down to deal a deadly blow to the beautiful maiden.  Instantly he stunned the orc with magik and rushed to put himself between the injured elf and danger.  This orc legionnaire was even harder than the previous orc and the battle raged for several long minutes, yet once again the man was able to defend the beautiful Maid from evil.&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;Well the man decided perhaps it would be best if the Maid walked in front of the man, then he could protect her cute little bottom.&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;&#8216;Grandpa!&#8217; the cute little girl laughed and playfully swatted him with her tiny hand on his worn battle armor, &#8216;you bad.&#8217;&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;Uhmph, the old dwarf laughed, &#8216;Well she was beautiful to look at as he followed her.  But suddenly two more legionnaires crashed through the underbrush and charged down the path, only this time they came from up the path and again attacked the maiden first.  The man again had to rush to interject himself between the Maid and danger and nearly fell as one legionnaire&#8217;s sword clanged against the man&#8217;s up held shield.  As the force of the blow resounded amid the trees, the man let out a grunt as the pain to the blow to his unprotected side landed solid against his ribs.&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;Well the Maiden eyes just seemed to flash in anger!  It was something to see!  Those pretty blue eyes blazing, she stopped one of the orcs completely!  As the man gave battle to the one before him, the Maid let off a flurry of magiks.  The orc&#8217;s eyes showed his quavering fear as he was suddenly much weaker and slower.  More and more of the man&#8217;s hammer blows crushed against him and he tried to run away in terror.  The man easily killed the orc with just a few more strikes against his gutless body.  The second orc was still just standing there, though the terror could be seen in his eyes!  The man rooted the orc with magiks then simple beat the helpless orc to death.  The foul villains!&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;The battle was short but very educational.  Alone, neither of them, man nor maiden would have survived the dangers of the path.  The cleric could not have killed without the aid of the enchantress and the enchantress could not of cast her magiks before their vile weapons would have cut her down.  It also taught them that one before the other was not the safest of ways.  No, it was much safer to travel side by side, shoulder to shoulder.&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;Well the path wound around the area and frequently their arms touched each other, though not intentionally mind you!  But soon their accidental touching became more pleasant and it was not long before they were laughing and chatting and even sometimes holding hands.  They talked of many things and shared many stories until the path stopped with two smaller paths branching off, one to the right and one to the left.  She had planned on taking the left path and he had planned on taking the right path.  They stopped and turned to face each other, he looking down into the beautiful slender elfin face.  He was no longer certain that he wanted to go down that path alone, and he could see by the look in her pale blue eyes that she too was uncertain of her desires.  The two touched hands together again, only this time it was intentional, a reaching out between man and maiden.  Her hand lifted slender fingers that caressed the man&#8217;s cheek and lips and he could not stop his own hand from reaching out to touch the trembling lips of the maiden.  In unison the hands came together, lips finally meeting and their embrace tight.  Man and Maiden seemed to fit together, he larger and stronger covering her frail slender body, she dainty and soft felt perfect within his arms and upon his chest.  As they stood there silently, he felt how soft she was, yet also felt how strong she was.  She was not a helpless young maiden, no, she was an enchantress with a backbone of determination, strength, and resolve.  He also learned he was not strong and mighty as he had thought he was.  His knees trembled just holding her! Then they parted, though still unwilling to loose the hold on the other&#8217;s hand.  The man and maiden looked down the paths that they had thought to travel.  Both seemed to lead in relative safety to whatever destinations life&#8217;s paths take them, yet to take either of the paths together was impossible.  Fingers entwined tightened and they chose neither path but stepped together out into the unknown.&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;Grandpa you funny! You not taller than Grandma so you could not look down into her &#8216;pretty eyes&#8217;!&#8217; The young elfin girl giggled.  Her tiny hands touched the garrulous old man&#8217;s face as she giggled.  &#8216;Dwarves are always shorter than Elves and you just a softie old dwarf&#8221; <br><br>&#8216;With that the old Elfin Enchantress, the old Dwarvin Cleric, and the small child laughed in the way only possible by the love of togetherness.&#8217;<br><br>I seemed to remember a touch to my body as I laid against the cold remains of the spider.  A breeze seemed to fill my mind and wisdom flowed freely.  Too I vaguely seem to picture old gray dwarven eyes looking at me then the swirl of healing that was far greater than anything I had yet been able to cast.  Yet when I rose from the dust, there was no one about me!  Nor was there any signs on my person that I had just fought a most deadly fight.  If it were not for the corpse of the spider, perhaps I would have felt myself insane.  Yet the remembrance of Riverdale was just as clear, though there was no proof to be seen!  I could not have imagined it for I had only once been to Riverdale and though promptly getting lost, soon departed the same way I entered.  Surely I would have remembered such a sight if I had truly witnessed it!<br><br>Confused I put one boot before the other, going to the river and washing the grime of death from person and weapon.  When I stood I glanced again to the site of my last battle, still nothing, just the bulk of the dead crag spider.  Slowly I turned away, that dream or vision bringing back the memory of that beautiful Elfin Maiden so many seasons and battles past.  It was a strange empty ache as I stepped unto the wooden bridge, one I knew neither the magiks of Enchantress or Cleric was ever going to be able to fill or heal.<br><br>As the man began to cross the bridge an Elfin Enchantress began to appear.  Then beside her appeared an old Dwarven Cleric and an old High Elf Enchantress with a young elfin girl standing between them<br><br>&#8216;Thank you Mother and Father.&#8217; The beautiful woman said.<br><br>&#8216;He isn&#8217;t much is he?&#8217; Grulos grunted.<br><br>&#8216;Not yet, but he could be.  After all you weren&#8217;t such a great cleric if I remember right at his age, without me around.&#8217;  Playfully and to the little girl&#8217;s delight the enchantress bonked the cleric&#8217;s helm with her rod.  &#8216;Remember?&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;Bah!&#8217; Grulos grunted, &#8216;he just isn&#8217;t good enough for Eylianna.&#8217;<br><br>&#8216;I got to hurry!  Love you.  Honey please be good and keep practicing.&#8217;  The elfin woman knelt and gave her daughter a huge hug.<br><br>&#8216;I will Mommie.&#8217; The girl said hugging her mother back in return.  How unjust had been the cruel fates that had stolen her father ere she knew him!<br><br>Without further ado, the man&#8217;s form was growing smaller with every step.  With a sound so faint as to be near silent, the enchantress once more took up the trail of the man.  Upon crossing the bridge she saw a lion patriarch sniffing the man&#8217;s footprints, tail twitching, a deep growl rumbling in its mighty chest.  But when Eylianna finished weaving her magik the lion simply blink and wander away.  A danger he had never even known.<br><br><br>Laleldil Tremulous<br>Thuloxe Paells  (one day I'll spell it correctly)<br>49 seasons a humble cleric<br>&lt;Order of Green Knights&gt;<br>&nbsp;<br>A simple cleric of Rodcet Nif on Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
