<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=10034729849905></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10034729849905><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=10034729849905>Upheavable at ten seasons</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=10034729849905#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=46685><span id=Scholar>Laleldil</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>78 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Oct 19th 2:29 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I sat one evening at the gates of Qeynos, the place perhaps of my birth.&nbsp;&nbsp;Although I still had no recollections of a Mother or a Father, I felt comfortable each time I entered the Temple and accepted education.  So to all intents and purposes Qeynos was my home.  As I sat there, I admired the new piece of jewelry that I had purchased from Chronchoker, an enchanter that wandered the area frequenty.  (You know that was so long ago I can't even remember what that shiny bit of metal and gem was?)  I felt though, and remember this well, how the gem, held in its precious metal workings, gave me an ability to accept even more of the magical flux that was so vital to casting the spells of healing.  I can also remember how I came to convince Chronchoker to sell me the jewelry at a substantial loss.<br><br>As I seemed to always be doing during my last couple of seasons, I was sitting in the tunnel just outside of the Burrow, healing and medding, simply to be faced again with yet more injured clamoring for heals.  It was a dificult time for me as I would have to gather every ounce of courage to step into that evil nest of gnolls and just as I would straighten my shoulders and work the tensions out of my arms with the swinging of my staff, new fighters would come crashing in around me and beg for heals with dire warnings given of a multitude of gnolls indiscriminately killing everyone in sight.  Chronchoker had entered the tunnel and watched me as I struggled to heal the others and heard my oft repeated wail of the inability I had to gather enough mana of life to heal all that needed healing.  I will never forget his generosity when he sold me the jewelry for the cash I had on me at the time, a few platinum pieces.<br><br>But that was really not the way this was to go.  For I was sitting there, just resting, relaxing and enjoying a few moments of idleness, when Sweepor, my friend a half dozen or better olser than I, dropped to his ankles and playfully knocked my book to one side.<br><br>"We are moving!  Come on!  Get Up!" He laughed as he bonked me on the head.  Naturally the thought of moving was not appealing to one such as I, I felt safe here!  But since he was going, there was little else I could do but leave with him.  The kindly priest in the temple comforted me in Qeynos, but he was never there beside me in the Burrows!  Stay and be forever alone or go and be with a friend in a strange place?  I make friends hard, so I had little choice.  When he said follow me, I did.<br><br>Please remember that to this point in my short life of ten seasons, I had only been in Qeynos, the Hills to the north, a few tremulous adventures into the depths of the Burrow, and one short jaunt to his homelands of Surefalls.  The only thing I knew of Western Karanas was that there was a werewolf that roamed frequently along the road near the Hills and he was something that could easily kill me.  My friend was always somewhere else with his older friends, and since I am not much of a boy of words, I never was with another that wanted to go to the Karanas.<br><br>Before we reached the Hills darkness descended all about us, (even today that seems to be the case whenever I need to travel, darkness of night or rain or both).  After a quick lesson, I learned how to follow him and still catch a glimpse of the strange and terrifying lands of Western Karanas.  Why was I terrified you ask?  Wasn't I with my friend and weren't both his other friends with us, all proven and well-armed?  Why did I not feel safe with a Lady Paladin, a mighty Warrior, and Sweepor a ranger?  It was not comforting to go down that narrow road in the dark and here Sweepor's reminiscing of his being caught by the werewolf right here and with all the corpses littering the area he might still be around.  It was not comforting that someone had cast on them some spell they called Spirit of Wolf, yet I had never even heard of that spell before.  No it was the most terrifying moment in my life when Bolaliel and Reiely disappeared in the darkness and I was left nearly alone with absolutely no idea where I was!  It was a mess trying to cross the Karanas, if I concentrated on using my new found skill at following, I would slam into a tree.  If I tried to avoid the trees, I would lose the ability to follow.  Not only did we eventually make it through Western Karanas, I then learned we needed to cross most of Northern Karanas.<br><br>Perhaps I hadn't studied enough geography in school, but I didn't know a Northern Karanas existed!  (I am glad Sweepor either didn't know of the Griffins or simply thought it best not to tell me about them.  If I knew then what I know now, I know I could never have made the run to a place called a druid ring.)  Nearly exhausted from the wild dash across this land of unknowns, I sat next to a tree.  I know it was a tree, I swear it!  But I also know I saw it moving and nothing like a tree that moves to the song of a mighty wind.  Jumping up I tried to find comfort with standing nearer my friends, but with a tree actually moving around, I heard a stranger say you have to 'group' with me for us to leave, and Sweepor warning that we needed to leave right now as danger was approaching from the northwest.<br><br>"Now Lal or we are all going to die!" Sweepor told me.  Now I had only 'grouped' with Sweepor a couple of times, three I think, and wasn't very adept at that simplest of functions, and I had spent most of my life all alone, so to speak.  Top that with a healthy portion of terror and I was nearly bawling trying to get it to work once again.<br><br>"Oh @#%^!"  Was the last thing I heard as suddenly the air seemed to split open around me, things that looked solid seemed to swirl all around me.  Yet nothing obscured that last sight I had as a bird-like creature screamed in furry right in front of me!<br><br>"Everybody ok?" Reiely laughed with unbridled excitement.  "That was close!"<br><br>"They said all we need to do is run east." Bolaliel said as he took off without further warning.  (If you get lost, just run east, you'll run right into Freeport, Sweepor told me.)<br><br>Thankfully I did manage to follow them, and as dawn began in front of me, I found myself 'bound' at the gates of a strange city.  Hardly had the dust settled when the other three decided they were going to the Oasis and all thought I should remain behind, being so young and all.<br><br>As I stood there and watched them go, I felt more alone than I had ever felt before.  Sure there were alot of people all around me but I felt utterly alone.  Orphaned apparently at birth, finding what solace I could find at the temple in Qeynos, at least I knew there which way was North. I knew I could kill a giant bat.  I could even kill a gnoll with my staff if I was careful enough.  When they disappeared, I had nothing to comfort me.  Was there even a temple in Freeport? Would Rodcife Nif know I was even here?<br><br>It was pitiful believe me.  I could get lost just going around a building.  Imagine my surprise when I 'zoned' and then had no idea where I was and couldn't even zone again.  To this day I have no idea how I got lost so quickly.  I guess I was the dumbest person in the world as I was so near the bank and actually going up to people and begging them for directions to the bank.<br><br>"Come on."  I turned at the sound of the voice.  It was the cleric, wise and mighty at 14 now, the one that had bound me at the gate.  I had seen him a couple of times in Qeynos and I admired him and his confidence.  Admired? No coveted!  He led me to the bank then slowly led me to the temple and then slowly took me to the entrance to West Freeport.<br><br>I heartfully thanked him for his patience and time.  Then a Lady gave me something, a pinkish gem.  She was a complete stranger to me.  I accepted the gift and thanked her for it, but didn't really appreciate what she had done.  It was just a gem, probably one she just didn't want anymore, though I certainly was poor enough that even a gold piece was cherished.  I stepped into the merchant's place of business and began to sell my bat wings, and rusty weapons, the last items from my adventures into the Hills and Burrow and was going to sell that gem too.<br><br>36 PLATINUM!  Good Praise what is this gem for?  So I quickly snatched it back from the eager grinning merchant and buried in deep in my Backpack.  I would never sell it!  To see who had given me this precious gem I questioned who all was in town at the time.  Standing near the bank were people 50 and near 60 seasons old!  The Lady who had given me the gem was 52 seasons old and a Priestess?  Though I diligently searched for her, and got lost more than a few times, I never did find her again to really express the gratitude I felt.  Surely I should give it back, and I would have tried, though I am sure she would have just laughed and sent me on my way.  It was her exceedingly great generousity that allowed me to purchase my 14th season spells.  I even now feel terrible that I cannot remember her name.  Though Damzing the cleric that bound me and led me around will never be forgotten.  Though Damzing isn't quite right I know if I ever see him again I will instantly know him...Damasing I think is closer. (Yes I did meet him many seasons later and his name I think is Damsing, I remembered to thank him again.  Funny how the past was so trivial to him, his deed so simple, he had no I idea why I was adament in my thanks.  He could not understand how his few brief minutes of caring had given me such great comfort.)  And Lady Priestess, should you ever read this, please accept my apology for not being so thankful that I should have been.  I tried for a long time to find you, but I could not.<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>A simple cleric of Rodcet Nif on Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
