<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100330735157890></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100330735157890><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100330735157890>A simple cleric</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=46685&mid=100330735157890#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=46685><span id=Scholar>Laleldil</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>78 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Oct 17th 4:29 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>FirstI would suggest you read many of the Journals of the Board.&nbsp;&nbsp;They are excellent!  Though I wish I were as adept a stroyteller I may never succeed in bringing the life of a cleric to such realistic proportions as Shrikke has done with the Shadow Knight and another Cleric has done, I will try to give the gists of my simple life.<br><br>Of course, as others must have, I never knew of my Mother and Father, I was just there one day, standing in the streets of Qeynos with a note in one hand and a wooden club in the other.  Once the note was taken from my trembling fingers, my life became a blur.  My instructions were clear, memorize the first spell of healing and the first spell of protection, I was warned, then prove myself a value to the God of Life - Rodcef Nif.<br><br>A value?  It was hard and bitter.  Death? It was frequent.  Fortunately Rodcef found enough favor in me to bring me back time and again.  Flippy loved to chase me and some Queen of the Fire Beetles loved to clamp her pincers about me and cut my frail young body in two.  Yet I grew, I learned, I scribed more spells, and called upon Rodcef Nif frequently to stike the foes that swarmed the open entrance to my new home.<br><br>Yet my friend, a ranger, waited impatiently, till patience grew thin and he left to adventure in to the bowels of the evil hole called Black Burrow.  I envied him his courage and skill, yet fear held me close to the only place I knew.  Until the day I, following him closely begging for yet another adventurous tale, saw him disappear in the middle of the street.  Confusededly I stepped forward and saw the path littered with the remains of young people I had recently spoke with!  Looking to the North, I just caught the last glimpse of my friend going over the hill as a Gnoll suddenly roared and attacked me.<br><br>His laughter when I spoke of my first adventure injured me greaviously and spurred me to perhaps my most ill-fated decision.  Alone I adventured to the Maw of BLack Burrow.<br><br>The carnage!  There within the narrow dark confines of the tunnel sat many that yet bleed from wounds.  Bodies broken and crushed!  My heart ached and I called forth the power and beg to be allowed to heal these injured souls.  Rodcef, in his wisdom, allowed precious little healing, yet it was enough.  The people smiled, rose, then disappeared!  I sat to contemplate and meditate this phenomena that the God of Life had shown me.  Just as I seemed to have been refilled with his blessings, warriors, casters, and asundry of other folk suddenly tumbled and fell to the dust upon which I sat.  It was the same people that had just so very recently smiled and disappeared!  For three solid days this happened, healing with the power of Life, meditating, only to be once more covered with the blood of the returning fighters bewailing the fate of others less fortunate that has been over run by a great 'train' of gnolls.<br><br>Fortunately, one might say, there was a pause to the carnage and I stepped where others had tread and saw the great pit before me.  At my feet I lay many I could only mourn, already they being far beyond any power so far bestowed upon me.  A voice of a friend called to me and urged me to enter the home of the Gnolls itself, to pass through a door and meet at a small bridge.  I diligently and cautiously followed the right wall, memorizing every detail should I need to flee for my life. <br><br>I passed through the door, went up a slight rise, and was attacked instantly by some scrawny gnoll.  In terror I turned to run and screamed in fright as elite gnolls burst through the door.  Near mindless, I ran, my only desire to see the open plains of the hills, sunlight, green grass!  I stumbled and crashed into and through the gnolls, frantically trying to open the door as their weapons slashed and their fist pummeled me.  Miraculously I found the way to the pit!  I knew I was steps away from safety.  No not the first opening in the wall, into the tunnel!  Yet in my terror I missed the tunnel and stepped into ... I do not know!<br><br>I fell and landed with a splash in some water.  Gnolls laughed in their snarls as I frantically swam to the far side.  My last glimpse of life was through the water becoming pink with my own blood as Razorgills began to consume me alive.<br><br>The Rodcef, in his humorous ways, set me back up naked and bid me get my corpse.  I, scared to death, managed to make it back to the Burrow and even avoided the gnolls that spawned there (thank you again kind people for dispatching those that appeared so quickly and efficiently).  I searched for a pool, yet found none!  I peered over the lip of the hole and studied the water far below, could I have somehow fallen down there?  I shuddered in fear, that slight movement enough to loosen the stones under my feet and I pummulted downwards.  I had no time to scream in terror!  I sunk below the surface and saw many corpses.  None appeared to be my scrawny little hide, though I had precious few seconds to search as the Gills once more relished the taste of young human flesh!<br><br>I sat in the streets of Qeynos and wept bitterly. Gone forever was that fantastic staff given to me by my friend.  Gone indeed was everything.  Though I had had no armor to speak of, I had taken most of my few platinum pieces that most regretable day and I faced life without weapon, armor, food and drink, and less than a handful of copper pieces.<br><br>"What's the matter now?" Sweepor laughed.<br><br>"I have nothing!  That great and wonderous staff you gave me from deep below those vile tunnels is gone!"  I dreaded to tell him that!  How great a value that weapon must have been to have been acquired with such a risk!<br><br>"I'll get your old corpse!"<br><br>"No!" I protested.  Surely I could not stand his death on my foolishness too!  Yet I could not convince him otherwise.  I had to follow, then wait anxietously for word of his most certain demise amongst an ever growing crowd of injured fighters of good against these vile blood thirsty gnolls.<br><br>"There is no pool." I heard him say as I laid my book to one side.  "You must have fallen into the pit."  <br><br>"No! I made sure to stay far from the edge of the pit!"<br><br>He stood there, uncertainly then said he would check to make sure.  He returned to inform me what I knew already, only my naked corpse was within the waters of that pit.  "There is only one other place you might have gone." I saw him shudder.  "I will get your corpse with your permission."<br><br>I begged him not.  "Would my death be worth you indecision to consent my pulling your corpse?  For I am going now to get it."<br><br>However he managed to recover my corpse I can only imagine, but I know one thing for certainty: do not go anywhere near that great tree with its hewn doorway!<br>&nbsp;<br>A simple cleric of Rodcet Nif on Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
